UGANDA CONTRACEPTION UPTAKE

Sheila

2023-12-11

Introduction

Uganda has one of the highest fertility rates in Sub-Saharan Africa. Advocacy for the use of contraceptives has been widely encouraged by the government to prevent unplanned pregnancies.However, several factors have influenced the uptake of contraceptives which include and not limited to the age,the religion of the individual,the mode of accessing information about the contraceptive, area of residence as well as the type of contraceptive.This study will be focusing on these various factors and how they have affected the use of the various contraceptive methods among women in Kampala.

Demographics

The study has a total of 18,506 women from Kampala coming from different types of residences both urban and rural. Where 14127 individuals came from a rural residence and 4379 came from urban residences. Below is a table showing a distribution of the participants among the different residences.

Contraception uptake

Adults who are not on any form of contraceptives are 10558 while the teenagers who are not on any contraceptives are a total of 2530. Hence 13% of the adult population was not on contraceptive and 47% of the teenage population was not any contraceptive.

Adults using contraceptives are 5073 while the teenagers using contraceptives are 132. This is 12.8% of the adult respondents who were on contraceptives and 0.08% of the teenagers were on contraceptives at the time of the interview.

The most used family planning method was injections with over 2506 participants while the least used family planning method was female condoms with only 2 participants.

Contraceptive uptake and age

Age has been shown to be influential in the type of contraceptive that is taken up.The boxplot below shows the contraceptive preference among the different age groups.

Contraceptive uptake and level of education

The level of education has been shown to affect the type of contraceptives that are used. Four of the highly used contraceptive methods were analyzed in line with the level of education to understand how this dynamic was expressed among the different participants. It was clear that individuals who had no education level had the lowest uptake of all the contraceptive methods. Participants whose highest level of education was primary used injections more than other methods followed by implants.This was also similarly seen by individuals whose highest level of education was secondary.Individuals who had a higher level of education seemed to prefer injections as well as male condoms.

Contraceptive use and religion

Religion has also been shown to affect contraceptive uptake.Four of the highly used contraceptives were again analyzed in line with the religion of the participants.It is clear that injections were highly used among most of the religions.Female sterilization was the least used.

Dissemination of contraceptive information

How the population receives information about contraceptives will determine the uptake of the contraceptives and the type of contraceptive that will be embraced. It is clear that information was most received by newspapers and least received by Television.

Conclusion

It is clear that a number of factors affect uptake of contraceptives and knowledge and consideration of these factors may enable creation of measures that may help with a more positive uptake of the various contraceptive methods.
